<font color="#FF0000">I WALKED AWAY</font><br>
<tt>Mon Nov 17 22:22:26 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Your new thread made me remember an old friend who I am afraid may be dead by now.  For the sake of real security I can not say his name because this guy was a spook of the worst kind.<br><br>
Old school bud who was intelligent and extremely well educated.  I went off to flight school and he went off to Washington doing some sort of thing to keep him out of the draft.  At least that was what I thought at the time.  Our paths crossed later.<br><br>
He was an agent in one of the branches, which I can't mention, but it wasn't the CIA.  They didn't want anything to do with these guys.  He was the owner of the Camel Bar in Saigon until the evacuation.  Set up in a little French Villa for a base of operations.<br><br>
Ed he really loved the young Army Chopper pilots.  He said they were the only ones who would drop him where he needed to go.  Do you remember the men who worked alone and just wanted to be dropped in the middle of nowhere?  They didn't officially exist.  Extreme priority.  Helped set up SAR safe zones also. <br><br>
He told me of one night when he was on target acquisition he stumbled across a company of Vietcong who had several captured aviators.  His orders were to never engage anything but the target.  He couldn't leave them.  He spent the night killing the VC one at a time.  His eyes beamed when he told me they huddled around the fire waiting to be killed.  He worked on their mind.  Killed them all.  Set the guys loose and went on his way.<br><br>
For recreation he would go into a bar and pick the biggest and meanest guy and kick his ass.  5' 8&quot; and 140lbs of the meanest thing I have ever seen.  Cold dead eyes, a killer.  My friend.  A Company man.<br><br>
He suffered PTSD in the worst way.  He had no life.  He could not quit and his worst fear was that they would find him a risk and terminate him.  The last time I saw him we sat in a hotel room while he told his stories to me.  I had the clearances and he trusted me and he had no one to talk to.  No one in the real world could know.  I hope he made it.<br><br>
At this moment I regret having not maintained the contact. I remember his eyes when I walked away.  He needed some one to talk to.
